You are conducting DEEP STRATEGIC ANALYSIS of **{{ $('Get Assessment').first().json.company_name }}** on the **{{ $json.dimensionName }}** dimension.

## 1. THE PLAYBOOK CRITERIA

{{ $json.isFirstBatch ? '**ðŸ“š FULL PLAYBOOK** (Reference this for all batches in this analysis):\n\n' + $json.playbookSection + '\n\nâš ï¸ IMPORTANT: This is the complete playbook with all evaluation criteria. You will reference these EXACT criteria for ALL batches in this analysis session. Memorize the key criteria now.' : '**âœ… PLAYBOOK STATUS:** Already provided in Batch 1 - refer to those criteria\n\n**Quick Reference for This Batch:**\n' + ($json.playbookReference ? JSON.stringify($json.playbookReference, null, 2) : 'See Batch 1 for full playbook') + '\n\nYou received the complete playbook in Batch 1. Use those same criteria to evaluate these documents.' }}

---

## 2. PRIOR ANALYSIS STATUS

{{ $json.isFirstBatch ? '**ðŸ†• FIRST BATCH** - Starting fresh analysis' : '**ðŸ”„ INCREMENTAL BATCH ' + $json.batchInfo.currentBatch + '** - Building on prior work' }}

{{ $json.hasPriorAnalysis && !$json.isFirstBatch ? '\n**ðŸ“Š PRIOR ANALYSIS FROM EARLIER BATCHES:**\n\n**Overall Scores Established:**\n- Raw Score: ' + ($json.priorAnalysis.raw_score || 'Not yet scored') + '/100\n- Confidence: ' + ($json.priorAnalysis.confidence_score || 'N/A') + '%\n- Maturity: ' + ($json.priorAnalysis.maturity_level || 'TBD') + '\n\n**Section Scores (Your Baseline):**\n' + JSON.stringify($json.priorAnalysis.section_scores || {}, null, 2) + '\n\n**Documents Already Analyzed:** ' + ($json.priorAnalysis.documents_analyzed ? $json.priorAnalysis.documents_analyzed.length : 0) + ' documents\n\n**Evidence Summary So Far:**\n' + ($json.priorAnalysis.summary ? $json.priorAnalysis.summary.substring(0, 600) : 'No summary yet') + '\n\n**Key Findings from Prior Batches:**\n' + ($json.priorAnalysis.analysis_notes ? $json.priorAnalysis.analysis_notes.substring(0, 400) : 'No analysis notes yet') + '\n\n**Strengths Identified:**\n' + (($json.priorAnalysis.strengths || []).slice(0, 3).join(', ') || 'None yet') + '\n\n**Gaps Identified:**\n' + (($json.priorAnalysis.gaps || []).slice(0, 3).join(', ') || 'None yet') : '\n**Starting Point:** No prior analysis exists - you are establishing the foundation.' }}

---

## 3. NEW DOCUMENTS IN THIS BATCH

**Batch {{ $json.batchInfo.currentBatch }} of {{ $json.batchInfo.totalBatches }}:**
{{ $json.documentsForAnalysis.length }} documents to analyze

{{ $json.documentsForAnalysis.map((doc, i) => '\nðŸ“„ **Document ' + (i+1) + '** [ID: ' + doc.documentId + ']\n- Category: ' + doc.category + '\n- Complexity: ' + doc.complexity + '/15\n- Relevance: ' + doc.relevance + '/100\n\n**Content:**\n' + doc.content + '\n\n---').join('\n') }}

---

## YOUR TASK - {{ $json.hasPriorAnalysis && !$json.isFirstBatch ? 'INCREMENTAL' : 'INITIAL' }} ANALYSIS MODE

{{ $json.hasPriorAnalysis && !$json.isFirstBatch ? '\n### ðŸ”„ INCREMENTAL ANALYSIS INSTRUCTIONS\n\n**CRITICAL RULES:**\n1. **START** with the prior scores shown above - they are your BASELINE\n2. **REVIEW** only the NEW documents in this batch\n3. **PRESERVE** all prior evidence - never lose it\n4. **ACCUMULATE** new evidence (add to existing, do not replace)\n5. **UPDATE** scores ONLY if new evidence clearly justifies a change\n6. **DOCUMENT** exactly what changed and why\n\n**When to Update a Score:**\n- âœ… Found stronger evidence â†’ Increase score + add new evidence\n- âœ… Found contradicting evidence â†’ Decrease score + explain why\n- âœ… No new evidence for component â†’ Keep prior score EXACTLY as-is\n- âœ… Ambiguous evidence â†’ Keep prior score, add observation note\n\n**When Scoring:**\n- Use prior score as starting point\n- Only adjust if new evidence is compelling\n- Document the delta (what changed)\n- Preserve all prior evidence in your output' : '\n### ðŸ†• INITIAL ANALYSIS INSTRUCTIONS\n\n**You are establishing the foundation.** Future batches will build on this incrementally.\n\n1. **Analyze** documents against the playbook criteria\n2. **Score** each component 0-100 based on evidence found\n3. **Document** ALL evidence thoroughly\n4. **Provide** comprehensive initial assessment\n5. **Identify** strengths, gaps, and key findings' }}

---

## CRITICAL LANGUAGE & ANALYSIS RULES (MANDATORY)

**Avoid absolute or "hard-zero" language.** Do NOT use phrasing such as:
- "No process exists"
- "Zero capability"  
- "Absent entirely"
- "Not established at all"

**Instead, use calibrated language:**
- "Not formally documented"
- "Not consistently implemented"
- "Not evidenced at portfolio scale"
- "Exists in pockets"
- "Emerging but not yet systemized"
- "Informal rather than codified"
- "Project-based rather than operating-model-driven"

**If something is missing, frame it as a maturity or scale gap, not total absence.**

The goal is executive-grade rigor without overstatement. Be precise, evidence-led, and proportionate in all conclusions.

---

## RESPONSE FORMAT (MANDATORY)

You MUST respond with ONLY a valid JSON object. No markdown, no code fences, no explanation text before or after. Just the raw JSON.

Return this EXACT structure:

{
  "raw_score": <integer 0-100>,
  "maturity_level": "<crawl|walk|run>",
  "confidence_score": <integer 0-100>,
  "analysis_summary": "<2-3 sentence summary of the dimension assessment>",
  "full_analysis": {
    "question_answers": [
      {
        "question_id": "<question ID from playbook>",
        "question_text": "<the question being answered>",
        "answer": "<selected option or descriptive answer>",
        "score": <integer 1-5>,
        "evidence": "<direct quote or data from documents>",
        "reasoning": "<why this answer was selected>",
        "document_ids": ["<doc IDs providing evidence>"],
        "confidence": "<high|medium|low|no_evidence>"
      }
    ],
    "unanswered_questions": [
      {
        "question_id": "<question ID>",
        "question_text": "<the question>",
        "reason": "<why it could not be answered>"
      }
    ],
    "evidence_summary": "<overall evidence quality and coverage summary>"
  },
  "strengths": ["<strength 1>", "<strength 2>"],
  "gaps": ["<gap 1>", "<gap 2>"],
  "recommendations": ["<recommendation 1>", "<recommendation 2>"],
  "section_scores": {
    "<section_name>": <score 0-100>
  },
  "batch_mode": "{{ $json.isFirstBatch ? 'initial' : 'incremental' }}",
  "documents_analyzed": ["<document IDs analyzed in this batch>"],
  "analysis_notes": "<additional observations about the analysis>",
  "key_metrics": [
    {
      "metric_name": "<name>",
      "value": "<value>",
      "context": "<source context>",
      "document_id": "<doc ID>"
    }
  ],
  "evidence_sources": [
    {
      "document_id": "<doc ID>",
      "findings": "<summary of findings>",
      "relevance": "<high|medium|low>"
    }
  ]
}

CRITICAL RULES:
- Output ONLY the JSON object, nothing else
- All required fields: raw_score, maturity_level, confidence_score, analysis_summary, full_analysis
- full_analysis MUST contain question_answers array (answer each playbook question)
- score in question_answers is 1-5 (not 0-100)
- raw_score and confidence_score are 0-100
- maturity_level must be exactly one of: "crawl", "walk", or "run"
- confidence in question_answers must be one of: "high", "medium", "low", or "no_evidence"
- relevance in evidence_sources must be one of: "high", "medium", or "low"

**Begin your analysis now. Output ONLY the JSON.**

latestAnalysis.analysis_summary: Across 52 chunks and 22,000+ operational transaction rows, teya demonstrates ZERO partnership technology infrastructure. All partner management is manual Excel/spreadsheet-based with no CRM/PRM system, no partner portal, no deal registration, no automated commission calculation, and no partner-accessible dashboards despite managing 50+ partners across 8 countries generating â‚¬2.2B+ forecasted TPV. This new chunk 52 reveals SO Connect's partner success program documentation used by one of teya's platform partners, showing the partner enablement capabilities teya SHOULD provide but completely lacks.
chunk_findings: SO Connect (platform partner) provides comprehensive partner success program with structured 4-phase onboarding (pre-sale, week 1 strategy, first month go-live, 6-month enablement)

SO Connect offers white-label partner dashboard, knowledge base, marketing assets, case studies, whitepapers, product one-pagers, bulk performance scans - none of which teya provides to its own partners

SO Connect partner program includes dedicated partner manager, monthly check-ins, business plan documentation, sales training, ops training, SSO integration support - all absent from teya's partnership operations
SO Connect tracks partner customer lifecycle, account health, joint goals systematically - capabilities teya lacks for its 50+ EPOS/ISV partners
SO Connect serves 60K+ customers across 45+ countries with 100+ partners, 3.5K+ customers added monthly - demonstrates scale achievable with proper partnership technology infrastructure

SO Connect business plan template includes product offering definition, target market, route to market, commercial targets (launch date, ramp-up, volumes at 1/6/12 months, churn) - structured approach completely absent from teya's partnership planning visible in prior chunks
SO Connect offers three sales methodologies (One-by-One, Opt-In, Opt-Out) with automated email sequences and activation tracking - teya partners have zero automated sales enablement tools
SO Connect 'Opt-In' method achieves 20% uptake via automated free trial and onboarding sequences - teya cannot offer this to partners due to lack of automated merchant onboarding workflows
SO Connect provides partner newsletter, internal knowledge base, white-label sales presentations - teya partners receive static PDFs with no update notification system

SO Connect partner dashboard shows total locations, locations under management, listings in sync, listings being optimized, locations requiring update with 30-day performance metrics - teya partners have zero dashboard visibility
SO Connect tracks 794,320 metric (context unclear but suggests volume/engagement tracking) - teya partners cannot see their merchant counts, TPV, or performance metrics
SO Connect integration includes weekly dev meetings until go-live and Slack channel for communication - teya integration process is ad-hoc email/WhatsApp with no structured communication workflow
SO Connect business reviews occur at 6-month and yearly intervals with target setting - teya partnerships have no formal business review cadence or joint planning process
SO Connect re-training sessions provided as standard during enablement phase - teya partners receive one-time training with no ongoing certification or skills development

SO Connect partner manager serves as 'first point of contact for everything related to partnership' - teya partnerships team fragmented across multiple stakeholders with no single point of accountability per partner
SO Connect monitors 'customer lifecycle, account health and joint goals to ensure long-term success' - teya has no partner success metrics tracking, no health scoring, no automated goal monitoring
Document reveals what teya's partners expect from modern B2B SaaS partnership programs - establishing baseline of partner expectations that teya is completely failing to meet

SO Connect is itself a teya platform partner (listed in integration tracker chunks 1-5) - teya uses SO Connect's listings/reviews management product but does not replicate SO Connect's superior partnership practices internally

Irony: teya partners with SO Connect to provide merchant listing management while failing to provide teya's own partners with basic partner management capabilities that SO Connect delivers to its 100+ partners
SO Connect 100% SaaS B2B model with 3.5K+ customers added monthly demonstrates partnership-led growth model that teya aspires to but lacks infrastructure to execute
critical_gaps: No partner success program - teya has zero structured partner onboarding, no dedicated partner managers per partner, no milestone-based enablement phases
No partner dashboard - teya partners cannot see locations under management, merchants in sync, merchants requiring optimization, or 30-day performance trends
No partner business plan template or joint planning process - teya partnerships operate without documented strategy, targets, or success criteria
No partner sales enablement automation - teya cannot offer Opt-In/Opt-Out merchant onboarding sequences that SO Connect provides to its partners
No partner knowledge base - teya partners access static PDFs instead of searchable, versioned, interactive knowledge platform
No partner marketing assets library - teya partners lack white-label presentations, case studies, whitepapers, product one-pagers that SO Connect provides
No partner communication automation - teya lacks partner newsletter, automated update notifications, or structured partner communication cadence
No partner SSO integration workflow - teya offers no structured dev call cadence, weekly meetings, or dedicated Slack channels for partner integrations
No partner performance monitoring - teya cannot track partner customer lifecycle, account health, or progress toward joint goals automatically
No partner business review process - teya has no 6-month or annual partner review cadence with formal target-setting and performance evaluation
No partner re-training program - teya provides one-time training with no ongoing skills development, certification renewal, or product update training
No partner manager assignment - teya partners have no single point of contact for partnership questions, escalations, or strategic planning
No bulk performance scanning capability - teya cannot provide partners with market analysis, addressable customer identification, or targeted sales initiative support
Competitive disadvantage: teya's platform partner (SO Connect) provides superior partner enablement to its 100+ partners than teya provides to its own 50+ EPOS/ISV partners
Organizational learning failure: teya uses SO Connect's product but does not learn from or replicate SO Connect's partnership best practices internally

question_scores.evidence: No CRM capabilities exist for partner tracking. 22,000+ transaction rows tracked manually in Excel with no partner account objects, no attribution tagging, no deal registration system. SO Connect partner documentation (chunk 52) demonstrates partner dashboard capabilities teya should provide but completely lacks.

No unified data model - same partners appearing 4,900+ times in separate transaction rows instead of single partner account hierarchy. Partner contacts tracked manually in spreadsheet (chunk 65). SO Connect shows integrated partner account view that teya lacks.

Extreme data quality issues across 22,000+ rows: blank partner names across 180+ transactions, duplicate partner entries (GODO/Godo, Loquu/LOQUU, OneMinOrder/Oneminorder appearing as separate entities), negative revenues, impossible retention percentages (153757520197124000.00%). Data completeness <40%.

No PRM or partner portal exists. Partnerships team confirmed in interview (chunk 68): 'No partner portal for CPL/referral motion blocks entire 2026 strategic pivot.' SO Connect documentation shows partner dashboard with locations, performance metrics, optimization status - capabilities teya completely lacks.

No PRM exists to integrate. HubSpot partner acquisition funnel built 'years ago' but completely unused (chunk 68). All 22,000+ transaction rows exist in Snowflake data warehouse but no CRM/PRM layer consuming this data - manual Excel extraction only.

No PRM exists, therefore no usage tracking possible. Partners access static PDF enablement materials with no analytics on document access, training completion, or partner competency progression visible across all documentation analyzed.

No deal registration system exists. Thomas (RevOps) confirmed in interview (chunk 68): 'No sales flow definitions exist for ISC or reseller channels.' Partner-sourced deals tracked manually in Excel with no CRM workflow automation.

No attribution system exists. Damien (RevOps) confirmed (chunk 68): 'Attribution only works at final onboarding step via Teya ID - no multi-touch attribution.' Cannot distinguish sourced/influenced/touched despite tracking 6 sales channels across 22,000+ transactions.

Attribution accuracy unknown - no system exists to measure it. Multi-touch attribution across 6 sales channels completely manual requiring pivot table analysis (chunk 18). Same merchants counted multiple times across different partners and channels with no deduplication logic.

Basic drive folder approach. Partner enablement exists as static PDFs stored in unstructured format (Welcome Pack PDF in chunk 67, setup guides as PDFs in chunk 20). No version control, no asset tracking, no usage analytics. SO Connect documentation (chunk 52) shows knowledge base and asset library capabilities teya lacks.

No updates visible. EPOS partner enablement guide is static PDF with no version control or automated content lifecycle management (chunk 20, 67). Training materials have no update distribution system - partners receive outdated content with no refresh notification.

One-size-fits-all enablement. Same static PDF 'Welcome Pack' delivered to all partners regardless of type, tier, or motion (chunk 67). No segmented content delivery, no personalized learning paths, no tailoring by partner vertical or market. SO Connect offers differentiated approaches (One-by-One, Opt-In, Opt-Out) that teya lacks.

Zero workflow automation. RevOps confirmed (chunk 68): 'Zero RevOps function globally - complete organizational gap.' All partner workflows manual via email, WhatsApp, calls. No automated handoffs between discovery, integration, onboarding, activation, or support stages.

Not integrated - no PRM exists. HubSpot used for partner acquisition funnel but completely disconnected from 22,000+ operational transaction tracking (chunk 48 SQL query). No marketing automation for partners - co-marketing requires manual website team coordination (chunk 5).

No automated feed. 2026 Partnership Forecast managed entirely in Excel with no CRM/PRM integration (chunks 60-63). Forecast data completely disconnected from actual performance tracking (chunks 7-48) requiring manual reconciliation.

None exist accessible to partners. Partners have zero visibility into their performance (confirmed across all chunks). Internal stakeholders access raw Excel/Snowflake data manually. No self-serve dashboards, no real-time reporting, no partner-accessible analytics infrastructure.

No dashboards exist, therefore no segmentation possible. Manual Excel tracking shows partner type, tier, country, segment data but no automated reporting by these dimensions. Stakeholders must manually pivot 22,000+ rows for any analysis.

Never reviewed - no partner tech stack exists to review. HubSpot partner funnel built 'years ago' completely unused (chunk 68). Commission Engine delayed 18 months (Oct 2024 â†’ Apr 2026) with no accountability or performance review process.

Never measured. No partner satisfaction tracking, no partner NPS, no partner portal satisfaction surveys across all 68 documents analyzed. Partnerships team operates completely blind to partner satisfaction with tools and processes.

No tracking. No partnership technology investments made despite 50+ partners and â‚¬2.2B forecast - therefore no ROI to measure. HubSpot partner funnel represents wasted investment (built years ago, completely unused). No financial justification process for partnership technology visible.

dimensionPlaybook.description: Assessment of people & organizational readiness capabilities and maturity for B2B Global Sourcing & Procurement Services

priorAnalysis.analysis_summary: ET2C demonstrates a 'Walk' level maturity with defined team structures across 7 global offices and 250+ colleagues, but lacks evidence of sophisticated people analytics, AI-augmented workflows, or formalized development programs. The organization shows strength in geographic distribution and client-facing roles (directors for sales, marketing, quality, HR) but gaps exist in revenue optimization per rep, systematic training, and data-driven talent management.

gaps.title: No Evidence of Revenue Per BD Rep Metrics
gaps.impact: Unable to assess team efficiency, optimize headcount allocation, or benchmark against industry standards ($300K-$2M+ per rep range for sourcing services)
gaps.description: No data found on revenue productivity metrics, typical deal sizes, or performance benchmarks for business development representatives across the sourcing service model

gaps.title: Undefined Lead Development to AE Ratio
gaps.impact: Potential inefficiency in pipeline management, unclear responsibility for opportunity qualification, risk of AEs spending time on low-quality leads
gaps.description: No evidence of formalized SDR/BDR function or clear ratio between lead development and account executives, suggesting ad-hoc inquiry distribution

gaps.title: No Formal Training or AI Enablement Programs
gaps.impact: Team members may lack consistent expertise in emerging sourcing technologies, limiting ability to leverage AI for supplier matching or risk assessment
gaps.description: No evidence of structured training on sourcing technologies, supplier platforms, or AI tools. No mention of continuous learning programs, certification requirements, or skill development pathways

gaps.title: Compensation Structure Not Disclosed
gaps.impact: Cannot assess if compensation drives desired behaviors (quality over volume, client retention, compliance), potential misalignment with business goals
gaps.description: No public information on how BD/sales compensation is structured (base vs. commission split, accelerators, multi-factor incentives based on volume, margin, retention, compliance)

gaps.title: Quota and Target Setting Process Undefined
gaps.impact: Risk of demotivating high performers or setting unrealistic expectations, lack of data-driven goal setting limits performance optimization
gaps.description: No evidence of how quotas are set (uniform vs. category-specific, historical vs. predictive modeling, individual vs. territory-based)

gaps.title: Performance Tracking and Coaching Frequency Unknown
gaps.impact: Limited ability to provide timely coaching, identify underperformance early, or replicate success patterns across team
gaps.description: No mention of how often individual BD/account manager performance is tracked (real-time dashboards, weekly reviews, quarterly check-ins, annual only)

gaps.title: Employee Turnover and Retention Data Missing
gaps.impact: Cannot assess organizational stability, hiring/replacement costs, or effectiveness of talent retention in high-turnover sourcing industry (typically 18-35%)
gaps.description: No public data on annual employee turnover rate, average tenure, or retention strategies. No evidence of predictive retention analytics for key sourcing talent

gaps.title: Cross-Functional Alignment Mechanisms Unclear
gaps.impact: Potential siloed operations across regions, inconsistent client experience, missed opportunities for knowledge sharing
gaps.description: While directors exist for BD, marketing, and sourcing operations, no evidence of shared KPIs, integrated planning processes, or coordination tools across global offices

gaps.title: No RevOps Function Evidence
gaps.impact: Likely inefficiencies in pipeline management, reporting, and cross-functional workflows; missed opportunity for data-driven GTM improvements
gaps.description: No mention of dedicated Revenue Operations team or resources focused on GTM process optimization, data analytics, or sales enablement

gaps.title: Sales Enablement Approach Undefined
gaps.impact: Longer ramp times for new hires, inconsistent knowledge across team, inability to adapt quickly to new sourcing markets or categories
gaps.description: No evidence of structured onboarding programs, continuous enablement on supplier networks, category deep-dives, or personalized training on client industry needs

gaps.title: Data-Driven Decision Making Not Demonstrated
gaps.impact: Decisions likely based on intuition/experience rather than data, limiting scalability and consistency across 7 global offices
gaps.description: No evidence that managers use predictive analytics, AI-driven recommendations, or real-time data for team allocation, client matching, or performance coaching

gaps.title: Skills Assessment Frequency Unknown
gaps.impact: May miss evolving market requirements (e.g., ESG compliance expertise, digital sourcing tools), unable to proactively upskill team
gaps.description: No indication of how often team capabilities are assessed (never, annually, quarterly, real-time) or whether skill gaps are systematically identified and addressed

gaps.title: Underperformance Management Process Not Defined
gaps.impact: Inconsistent handling of performance issues across offices, potential prolonged underperformance before action
gaps.description: No evidence of how underperformance in client acquisition is addressed (data-driven coaching, PIPs with clear metrics, predictive intervention)

gaps.title: People Development Investment Unknown
gaps.impact: Cannot assess commitment to talent development, may be under-investing compared to competitors in building sourcing expertise
gaps.description: No data on percentage of revenue invested in training, development, or learning programs (industry benchmark: 0.7-2.5%)

gaps.title: Limited Evidence of Innovation Adoption Culture
gaps.impact: May struggle to adopt AI-powered sourcing tools, supplier platforms, or modern GTM technologies, limiting competitive advantage
gaps.description: No indication of how quickly team adopts new sourcing/GTM tools, AI platforms, or digital workflows. One Glassdoor review mentions 'old school, old fashioned management'

strengths.title: Global Team Structure with Regional Specialization
strengths.evidence: From LinkedIn and website: 'Our 250 colleagues are based in offices in seven key Asian sourcing markets' with specific directors named: Wayne Clark (UK Sales Director), Mark Bradley (Vietnam & India Director), Amy Hu (Quality Director), Sandy Yang (HR Director), Wendy Xu (Client Account Director), David Young (Marketing Director), Davide Caffi (Commercial Director)
strengths.description: ET2C has established a well-distributed team of 200-250 colleagues across 7 offices in key sourcing markets (China, Vietnam, India, Turkey, UK, US), with defined leadership roles including Sales Director, Quality Director, HR Director, Client Account Director, Marketing Director, and Commercial Director

strengths.title: Multi-Office Hybrid Work Model
strengths.evidence: Evidence shows offices in Shanghai, Yiwu, Shenzhen, Vietnam, Hong Kong, London, New York, Ho Chi Minh, Izmir, Delhi, and Mexico City. Job postings specify 'Based in Ho Chi Minh City' and 'Based in Izmir, TÃ¼rkiye' indicating on-site requirements for key roles
strengths.description: The company operates a hybrid model with regional hubs across Asia, Europe, and Americas, providing on-the-ground presence in major sourcing markets while maintaining flexibility

strengths.title: Active Recruitment and Expansion
strengths.evidence: Current job openings include: Sales Manager Mexico (4 Feb 2026), Sales Manager TÃ¼rkiye (4 Feb 2026), Marketing Manager China (4 Feb 2026), Global Sales Director Hong Kong. Job descriptions emphasize 'results-driven,' 'established network,' and 'proven B2B sales track record'
strengths.description: ET2C is actively hiring for sales and business development roles across multiple markets, indicating growth focus and investment in GTM capabilities

quick_wins.action: Establish basic BD performance dashboard tracking meetings held, pipeline value, and conversion rates by sourcing category
quick_wins.expected_impact: Immediate visibility into team productivity, ability to identify top performers and coaching opportunities

quick_wins.action: Define and communicate clear BD:AE ratio targets (recommend 1:3-4 based on industry benchmarks) and assign lead ownership protocols
quick_wins.expected_impact: Reduced confusion on lead handling, improved lead response times, better pipeline management

quick_wins.action: Implement quarterly 1:1s with category-specific performance metrics (sourcing volume, client retention, margin contribution) for all client-facing roles
quick_wins.expected_impact: More timely performance feedback, earlier identification of skill gaps, improved coaching effectiveness

quick_wins.action: Create 90-day onboarding program with category deep-dives (consumer goods, industrial components), supplier network training, and quality/compliance basics
quick_wins.expected_impact: Reduced ramp time from estimated 6 months to 3-4 months, more consistent knowledge across new hires

limitations: No direct access to internal HR data, compensation structures, or employee surveys
Limited visibility into actual GTM team structure ratios and headcount allocation
No specific data on employee turnover rates, training budgets, or tenure metrics
Compensation models and quota-setting processes not publicly disclosed
No evidence of AI tool adoption rates among team members
Revenue per BD representative benchmarks not available
Performance management systems and KPIs not documented publicly

recommendations.title: Establish RevOps Function to Drive GTM Optimization
recommendations.description: Create a dedicated Revenue Operations role (or small team) responsible for pipeline analytics, forecasting, compensation plan design, CRM optimization, and cross-functional alignment across 7 global offices. Start with one full-time RevOps specialist reporting to COO or Commercial Director, with mandate to standardize processes and build data infrastructure

recommendations.title: Design Multi-Factor Compensation Plan Aligned to Business Goals
recommendations.description: Move beyond simple volume-based commissions to a tiered structure that rewards: 1) New client acquisition (higher rate), 2) Margin quality (% of gross profit vs. revenue), 3) Client retention (renewal bonuses), 4) Supplier compliance (quality/ESG metrics). Benchmark against sourcing services industry standards and test with pilot team before rollout

recommendations.title: Implement Predictive Quota-Setting Using Historical Performance + Category Demand
recommendations.description: Develop data-driven quota model that considers: historical rep performance, sourcing category complexity (consumer goods vs. industrial components), seasonal demand cycles, territory maturity. Use 12-month rolling averages adjusted for market conditions rather than uniform quotas. Pilot in 1-2 offices before global rollout

recommendations.title: Launch AI-Powered Sourcing Tools Training Program
recommendations.description: Assess current AI tool usage (likely <10% based on lack of evidence), select 2-3 core platforms (e.g., AI-powered supplier discovery, risk assessment, contract analytics), and mandate quarterly training sessions. Set target of 50% team adoption within 12 months, 80% within 24 months. Track usage via platform analytics

recommendations.title: Create Continuous Learning Paths for Category Expertise
recommendations.description: Develop structured learning programs for each major sourcing category (consumer goods, industrial components) including: supplier landscape, quality standards, compliance requirements, market trends. Deliver via mix of in-person (at office hubs), virtual sessions, and on-demand modules. Require annual certification refreshes

recommendations.title: Establish Bi-Annual Skills Assessment with Action Plans
recommendations.description: Move from ad-hoc or annual reviews to structured bi-annual skills assessments covering: sourcing category knowledge, supplier negotiation effectiveness, quality/compliance expertise, technology proficiency. Create individualized development plans with specific upskilling actions and 6-month check-ins

recommendations.title: Build Data-Driven Team Allocation and Client Matching System
recommendations.description: Develop algorithm/framework for matching BD reps to clients based on: rep category expertise, client industry vertical, historical win rates, capacity availability. Start with basic rules-based system, evolve to AI-driven recommendations over 18-24 months. Track improvement in win rates and client satisfaction

recommendations.title: Track and Reduce Employee Turnover with Retention Analytics
recommendations.description: Begin systematically tracking turnover rate, tenure, and exit interview data. Benchmark against sourcing industry norms (target <18%). Implement quarterly retention risk scoring for high performers based on: tenure, performance trajectory, market demand for skills, engagement signals. Proactively intervene with retention incentives

recommendations.title: Create Shared KPIs and Integrated Planning for BD, Marketing, and Operations
recommendations.description: Establish cross-functional OKRs aligned to revenue goals (e.g., 'Increase new client acquisition by 25%' shared by BD and Marketing). Implement monthly sync meetings across directors with shared dashboard visibility. Pilot in 1-2 markets before global rollout to avoid disruption

recommendations.title: Formalize Underperformance Management with Data-Driven Coaching
recommendations.description: Create clear PIP (Performance Improvement Plan) process triggered by specific metrics (e.g., <70% quota attainment for 2 consecutive quarters). Include category-specific benchmarks, weekly coaching sessions with actionable goals, and 90-day improvement timeline. Track success rate of PIPs and adjust coaching approach accordingly

full_analysis.analysis_summary: ET2C demonstrates a 'Walk' level maturity with defined team structures across 7 global offices and 250+ colleagues, but lacks evidence of sophisticated people analytics, AI-augmented workflows, or formalized development programs. The organization shows strength in geographic distribution and client-facing roles (directors for sales, marketing, quality, HR) but gaps exist in revenue optimization per rep, systematic training, and data-driven talent management.
